 Herness Engi

1. The harness is separable from and consequential beyond the underlying model: with the same model, harness/scaffolding changes alone have been documented to swing coding-benchmark performance dramatically (e.g., from 42% to 78% on SWE-Bench), evidence that the harness contributes capability measurably distinct from the model itself. [particula-agent-scaffolding-swebench]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
2. Coding harnesses differ in their top-level control architecture. Claude Code runs an LLM-driven loop of three blended phases — gather context, take action, verify results — serving as the agentic harness (tools, context management, execution environment) around the model. By contrast, the research_agent harness deliberately does NOT use an LLM-driven ReAct loop at the top level: it runs a deterministic six-stage pipeline — [1] intake & classify, [2] plan/discovery, [3] collect (parallel fan-out), [4] synthesize, [5] verify (independent), [6] report — sequenced by a Python orchestrator rather than by the model. [claude-code-docs-how-it-works, PLAN-general-research-agent.md]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
3. The iterative tool-use ('agentic') round-trips within a single step are delegated to the SDK's per-call query() loop rather than hand-rolled; stateless workers behave like functions so the orchestrator sequences them instead of trusting a long conversation, which prevents stale-context leakage and dropped tool round-trips. [PLAN-general-research-agent.md]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
4. The single most important factor in tool performance is an extremely detailed description (aim for 3-4+ sentences) covering what the tool does, when it should and shouldn't be used, each parameter's meaning, and caveats. Good interfaces consolidate related operations into fewer, more capable tools (e.g., an `action` parameter rather than separate create_pr/review_pr/merge_pr) and use meaningful service namespacing (e.g., github_list_prs, slack_send_message) to reduce selection ambiguity as the library grows. [anthropic-define-tools, anthropic-writing-tools-for-agents]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
5. Tool responses should return only high-signal information and stable semantic identifiers (slugs/UUIDs) rather than opaque internal references, since bloated responses waste context; token efficiency can be achieved through pagination, range selection, filtering, and truncation, and a response_format enum can let the agent request 'concise' or 'detailed' output. [anthropic-define-tools, anthropic-writing-tools-for-agents]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
6. The built-in text editor tool is str_replace-based rather than unified-diff-based. It supports view (read/inspect), str_replace (search-and-replace requiring the old_str to match exactly including whitespace/indentation), create (full-file write), and insert (line-targeted insertion). The undo_edit command was removed for Claude 4 text editor versions (text_editor_20250429), leaving view, str_replace, create, and insert. [anthropic-text-editor-tool]
   _Caveat: may be outdated (published 2025-04-29); not peer-reviewed._
7. str_replace edits are validated by requiring exactly one matching location: multiple matches are rejected ('Found N matches... provide more context') and no match is rejected ('No match found'), while a successful edit confirms replacement at exactly one location. The tool is schema-less (its schema is built into the model and cannot be modified) and is applied by the host application, which is responsible for executing the file operation and enforcing security such as path validation against directory traversal, backups, error handling, and permission checks. [anthropic-text-editor-tool]
   _Caveat: may be outdated (published 2025-04-29); not peer-reviewed._
8. In Claude Code, the project/user instruction files and the system prompt are distinct layers: CLAUDE.md content is injected as a user message AFTER the system prompt (shaping behavior as context, with no guarantee of strict compliance) rather than being part of the system prompt; instructions wanted at the system-prompt level must be supplied via --append-system-prompt on every invocation. [claude-code-docs-memory]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
9. The research_agent harness has only a single provider seam — an injectable QueryFn callable (Callable[..., AsyncIterator[Any]]) defaulting to the real claude_agent_sdk `query` and swappable for tests — rather than a multi-provider adapter layer; every stage is built on claude_agent_sdk. Provider-agnosticism is limited to output parsing: helpers are kept provider-agnostic and dependency-free (concatenating text blocks, tolerating prose/code-fences around JSON), not an abstraction over different LLM backends. Model and credential selection are delegated to the installed `claude` CLI driven through the SDK; the harness loads ANTHROPIC_API_KEY from .env and sets no model= argument in any ClaudeAgentOptions builder. [research_agent/collectors.py, research_agent/parsing.py, research_agent/cli.py]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
10. Parallel fan-out in the research_agent harness spawns one stateless collector subprocess per sub-question/axis inside an anyio task group, bounded by a semaphore (DEFAULT_MAX_CONCURRENCY = 8) so a broad request cannot exhaust file descriptors or hit rate limits. Results preserve input order, each sub-question yields exactly one CellResult (none silently dropped), and a single failing collector is isolated — its exception is caught and recorded on that cell's CellResult.error rather than aborting the whole fan-out. Collectors carry no resume/session_id, so the orchestrator (not a transcript) owns sequencing and gating. [research_agent/collectors.py, PLAN-general-research-agent.md]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
11. Result aggregation is done in orchestrator code: per-cell findings from the parallel collect stage are flattened into one list and persisted, then passed as structured data through synthesis and verification with the code-enforced synthesis-before-report and verify-before-report gates between stages. [research_agent/orchestrator.py]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
12. The research_agent harness treats SDK session transcripts as disposable and the structured Finding/Claim records as the source of truth. State is checkpointed to disk as one directory per run containing findings.jsonl, claims.jsonl, and a checkpoint.json manifest (run_id, finding/claim counts, ISO timestamp), so a run survives a process restart; records are serialized one-per-line as JSONL (reading a missing file returns an empty list), and a fresh ProvenanceStore for the same run_id/base_dir reads back identical data. [store.py, research_agent/store.py]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
13. Resumption in the research_agent harness never replays the transcript. resume_research() loads the saved run, re-validates freshness FIRST, and rebuilds synthesis before continuing through the same verify/report gates. Staleness is detected by comparing each finding's captured source version against the current version from a source-of-record function; a mismatch marks the finding stale. revalidate() partitions saved findings into fresh vs. stale, re-collects only the superseded branch, and rebuilds synthesis from refreshed inputs (since derived findings cannot outlive their inputs), and if no claim survives the rebuilt run is again blocked with ReportBlockedError. Each Finding captures published date and version (or content hash) at the collect stage precisely because these enable later freshness checks and cannot be reconstructed afterward. [orchestrator.py, research_agent/orchestrator.py, store.py, research_agent/store.py, types.py, research-stale-session-revalidation.md]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
14. The governing principle behind resume behavior is that a saved session is frozen, point-in-time evidence, not live evidence; resuming re-injects snapshots as if current, so the system validates each finding's provenance against the system of record, re-collects the superseded branch, invalidates every derived finding (synthesis included), and continues from a clean checkpoint rather than resuming a transcript whose tool-results can no longer be vouched for. [research-stale-session-revalidation.md, research_agent/store.py]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
15. Session-hygiene helpers encode that a resumed session restores Claude's memory of external state but not the state itself: build_refresh_instruction names exactly which external surfaces changed and forces a re-read/diff (flagging prior conclusions that no longer hold) before continuing; should_start_fresh decides when to abandon resume; fresh_session_options starts clean with a vetted summary as the system_prompt after a structural change; and fork_for_parallel_analysis forks at a checkpoint for independent analyses. [session.py, research_agent/session.py]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
16. The research_agent harness recovers from malformed model output defensively rather than crashing. JSON extraction first tries a strict parse, then falls back to slicing between the first '{' and last '}' to tolerate prose/code-fences, raising a typed ParseError only when no object can be recovered. A collector returning empty or unparseable output raises a typed CollectionError (wrapped with the collector id) rather than silently accepting an empty answer. The verifier fails closed: empty content, unparseable JSON, or an unknown verdict string each resolve to an UNSUPPORTED verdict with an explanatory reason, so a broken check cannot launder a claim into the report. [research_agent/parsing.py, research_agent/collectors.py, research_agent/verifier.py]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
17. The research_agent codebase enforces a verification gate in two senses. As CI/process verification, the same gate — ruff lint, mypy --strict (over the research_agent package), and pytest — runs in GitHub Actions on every push and PR (env synced --frozen to uv.lock) and in a local pre-commit hook before every commit, as documented in the README. As an in-application loop, each claim is re-checked by a structurally independent fact-checker in fresh context returning supported/unsupported/overstated; only 'supported' claims reach the report (else ReportBlockedError), the verifier fails closed, and a freshness/re-collection feedback loop re-collects stale branches, rebuilds synthesis, and re-runs the same verify/report gates. [ci.yml, pre-commit-config.yaml, README.md, pyproject.toml, verifier.py, orchestrator.py]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
18. This Claude Agent SDK harness supports asynchronous/background execution as a first-class capability. Background bash commands run detached, persist across turns, and re-invoke the agent on exit (no '&' needed; foreground sleep is blocked). Subagents can run asynchronously with notification on completion, and concurrency is achieved by issuing multiple independent tool calls in a single message. Workflows run in the background, returning immediately with a task ID and a task-notification on completion, with concurrent agent() calls capped at min(16, cpu cores − 2) (excess queued) and a lifetime cap of 1000 agents. [harness-tool-bash, harness-tool-agent, harness-tool-workflow]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._
19. Background work in this harness is managed by a task-tool family: TaskStop terminates a running background task by ID; background tasks write output to a file path returned in the tool result (the same path arriving in a task-notification on completion), and TaskOutput can block to wait for completion or check status non-blocking. The Monitor tool runs a background script whose stdout lines become notifications arriving while the agent keeps working, with persistent monitors running for the session lifetime until TaskStop or session end. [harness-tool-taskstop, harness-tool-taskoutput, harness-tool-monitor]
   _Caveat: not peer-reviewed._

